The Liberty Hills () are a line of rugged hills and peaks with bare rock eastern slopes, about long, standing northwest of the &lt;a href="Marble%20Hills"&gt;Marble Hills&lt;/a&gt; and forming part of the west wall of &lt;a href="Horseshoe%20Valley%20%28Antarctica%29"&gt;Horseshoe Valley&lt;/a&gt;, in the &lt;a href="Heritage%20Range"&gt;Heritage Range&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="Ellsworth%20Mountains"&gt;Ellsworth Mountains&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="Antarctica"&gt;Antarctica&lt;/a&gt;. The Liberty Hills were mapped by the &lt;a href="United%20States%20Geological%20Survey"&gt;United States Geological Survey&lt;/a&gt; from ground surveys and &lt;a href="U.S.%20Navy"&gt;U.S. Navy&lt;/a&gt; air photos, 1961–66. The name was applied by the &lt;a href="Advisory%20Committee%20on%20Antarctic%20Names"&gt;Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names&lt;/a&gt; in association with the name Heritage Range. The remarkable &lt;a href="High%20Nunatak"&gt;High Nunatak&lt;/a&gt; towers east of the Hills.
